        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The estimated angular separation between the recoiling SMBH and host galaxy center ranges from 0.1 to 0.4 arcseconds.  Beam size of 0".05 in band 6 C36-7 configuration will be sufficient to resolve separation. 
The estimated angular separation between the recoiling SMBH and host galaxy center ranges from 0.1 to 0.4 arcseconds.  Beam size of 0".05 in band 6 C36-7 configuration will be sufficient to resolve separation. The largest scale for dense molecular gas (circumnuclear disk) probed with HCH(4-3) in NGC 1068 (Sey 2) is about 0.5 kpc, and 0.5 kpc at z=0.14 corresponds to 0.2". We choose twice of this as a LAS.

</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Requested RMS:
Our recoiling SMBH candidates are all LIRGs or ULIRGs with broad emission lines and very similar to local ULIRG QSO Mrk 231. So, we used published Mrk 231 HCO+(3-2) flux density in Fig. 2. of Aalto et al. (2015).
They used IRAM PdBI with beam size of 0".39 x 0".35 and ALMA band 6 C36-7 configuration beam size is 0".05.
Their flux needs to be rescaled to our sample with (d_L(Mrk231)/d_L(candidate))^2, where d_L represents luminosity distance.
Line width of the HCO+(3-2) estimated from Aalto et al. (2015) is 235 km/s and bandwidth we want to select is 40 km/s (6 spectral bins). In our sample, the smallest velocity offset between the recoiling SMBH and systemic velocity is 80 km/s and will have 2 spectral bin difference.
If we want 5 sigma detection of the HCO+(3-2) in recoiling SMBH candidate, the sensitivity will be:

Integrated flux at recoiling SMBH radius (boundary between recoiling SMBH carrying BLR and left-over NLR) * (beam_PdBI/beam_ALMA)^2 * (d_L(Mrk231)/d_L(candidate))^2 / number_spectral_bin / number_sigma
= 12.72 Jy / beam / km^-1 * (0.05/0.37)^2 * (186.4 Mpc/746.6 Mpc)^2 / 6 / 5
= 0.483 mJy.

HCN(3-2) line is about twice stronger than HCO+(3-2), so we can achieve about 10 sigma detection for this line (&gt; 10 sigma for recoiling SMBH having blue-shifted velocity and about 10 sigma for NLR having systemic velocity).

</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
